Finding Best Performance Window

A stock analyst in Chennai tracks daily profit/loss values in an array. They want to find the best consecutive period of exactly k days that gives the maximum average profit.

Given an integer array nums and an integer k, find a contiguous subarray of length k that has the maximum average value, and return that average.

Note: The subarray must be exactly length k, not smaller or larger

Input format :
First line: integer n
Second line: n space-separated integers
Third line: integer k
Output format :
First line: Max Average: x
Second line: Subarray indices: l r
Code constraints :
1 <= n <= 10^5
1 <= k <= n
-10^4 <= nums[i] <= 10^4
Answer precision within 1e-5 is acceptable
Sample test cases :
Input 1 :
6
1 3 2 6 4 5
3
Output 1 :
Max Average: 5
Subarray indices: 3 5
Input 2 :
6
1 12 -5 -6 50 3
4
Output 2 :
Max Average: 12.75
Subarray indices: 1 4




Solution:



#include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main(){
    int n;
    cin>>n;
    
    vector<int>nums(n);
    
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
        cin>>nums[i];
    }
    
    
    int k;
    cin>>k;
    
    int sum = 0;
    
    int max_average = 0;
    
    int left = 0;
    for(int right = 0;right < n;right++){
        
        sum += nums[right];
        
        if(right-left+1 > k){
            
            int average = sum / k;
            
            max_average = max(max_average,average);
            
            sum -= nums[left];
            left++;
        }
    }
    
    cout<<max_average;
    cout<<endl<<
}
